After the stock exchange closed, the Prague Stock Exchange went down.
After the crash on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange has recovered its losses.
The transactions with ČEZ shares amounted to almost half of the usual daily transactions.
On Tuesday, as the market began to open, the Prague stock market continued its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in Wall Street stocks.
The market reaction to the outcome of the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan for the stabilisation of the US financial sector, is thus also perceptible in our country.
Shares fall in Asia
Asian stock markets fell dramatically on Tuesday, although the indices managed to erase some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng index of the Hong Kong stock exchange lost four percent during trading, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index tracking the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange fell 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange was losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
Its index showed the Taiwan stock market down 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation over the US bailout will affect financial markets around the world", observed Joseph Yam, the head of the Hong Kong monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said US lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to shore up the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could be affected.
The bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, which would have required spending up to $700 billion.
The lawmakers thus denied President George Bush's call for support for the bill.
Bush said the project would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks were in a bloodbath Monday, and major stock indexes suffered their biggest decline in 20 years.
The Dow Jones lost nearly seven percent, the last time it fell so far in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress caved in: the US government can inject $ 700 billion into the banks
Leaders in the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed to a broader form of financial aid agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a breakthrough in the talks to adopt a bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion bailout of the U.S. financial system.
Success is not guaranteed.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the bill and put it to a vote, Congressmen must finish a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be considered in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
Sources say the plan is expected to be put to a vote in the Senate on Wednesday at the earliest.
Economists say that the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be the first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market support can be effective, a 'disillusionment' will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form the package of measures for market stabilisation should take", Democratic Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
The final vote could take place as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislature met with the U.S. Secretary of the Treasury Henry Paulson to give the government's budget a final shape.
The latter should buy back from financial companies the unsellable real estate assets which cause considerable losses to financial companies and threaten the stability of the whole system.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The plan to re-establish the markets still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there", says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are working to get Congress to reach a final agreement by Sunday.
They are hoping to calm investors before trading begins on Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect trading on Monday.
It is impossible at the moment to say with certainty when the two houses of the US Congress will vote, or whether the negotiations will be blocked at the last moment by some problem or another.
Lawmakers hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount of aid for the scheme must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be made available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its purpose, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr Bush welcomed the progress in the negotiations
While the president can veto the decision, Congress has the option to veto the decision.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain funds to buy back bad real estate, whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed with the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Mr Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on accountability for the financial program, protection of contributors from losses, settlement of impairments, the timing of the plan.
The new law also provides for a limit on the use of the golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to monitor the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also provides for assistance for property owners who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new installments for mortgages it is going to buy, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to Patria Finance's chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"This is because the mechanism and price of the repurchase of the problem assets are unknown.
This will be a key point in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government", Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is, according to Marek, not so important.
"It is much more important that the members of Congress agree, as early as this week, that they support this plan and that they will pass it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is the most important thing at the moment", Marek stressed.
A battle that went to the extreme: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We'll advise you how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
There are, however, good reasons for acquiring a standalone reader.
The choice of the material depends entirely on the future owner's requirements and the way it is used.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end gramophone for the house to play the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
If you have a stack of vinyl records in your home, with art rock, jazz, or blues music on them, you are probably at least dreaming of such a phonograph.
The same applies to music on the move, compressed music, to put it simply, MP3 music.
Here, too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty withholding headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
There's a lot to choose from.
Battery life is also crucial
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobile phones.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to basic functions, such as telephone calls and text messages, it can play music and movies, record them, has a camera of varying quality and can even be used for navigation.
And if you factor in smartphones and communicators, you'll have a little computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take pictures, we are witnessing a miracle.
The universal nature of the mobile, however, is not without its drawbacks.
The greater the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two recharging times.
And playing music is one of the most important energy-consuming activities.
Few mobile phones are capable of playing music for ten to twelve hours, and in most cases, this figure is much lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the more rudimentary ones) are clearly more efficient.
In the case of cheap cell phones, expect them to play music for only a few hours.
If you also call from time to time, get a second charger for work - even for more expensive devices.
This will not be a problem for MP3 players, which can be charged for at least 9 hours of continuous operation, including the least powerful ones.
Another problem arises when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all of them can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly onto the memory card, but few card readers are able to do this without reduction, given the tiny size of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As for the readers, you don't need any software, except for (iPod).
All you have to do is fill the USB connector with the music device from the computer.
Most mobile devices and players will create their own media library sorted by artist name, album title, style, or user judgment.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, similar to Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, you should be interested in the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of the sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If music is essentially background noise for you and you're only going to listen to it for a limited time during the day, for example, when you take the tram, you can use any mobile device that plays MP3s.
Virtually every mobile phone today is capable of this.
You don't even have to worry too much about what music formats your mobile or player can read.
Everyone can play MP3s, and the vast majority of the music that you're going to get is going to be in that format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding mobile phone operator's (or other provider's) web pages and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
Unfortunately, the supply of operators is very limited and in most cases limited to fast-moving radiotubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, Internet, or even wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still carry their motive around with them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just take your phone out of your pocket, while you left your MP3 player at home.
It is also important whether you always carry headphones or a handsfree device with a connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which are available in almost all mobile phones, but at least MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile music devices is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three grand.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can have a Walkman that is already very suitable.
But in most cases, you'll be limited by the lack of a standard headphone output.
The best phones and the best equipped ones, with a regular headphone jack, cost no more than fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of easy operation.
Anyone can order the most basic readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest ones (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the control with that of a cassette recorder, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet accidentally connected, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (such as the M2, microSD, and so on).
Even if you take into account the additional cost of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones even manage to get by with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, get a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 SEK.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose instead specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series of mobile phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the furthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price range, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
The first virtual operator will enter the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe you can .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their counterparts in Western Europe.
However, we are still lacking something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower their prices.
He may not be gone for long.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) has reported that the price of SMS is higher in the Czech Republic than in the rest of the EU, and it has confirmed this.
The latest steps by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges are likely to create a paradox - SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we have three mobile networks and a penetration rate well in excess of 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is making a deal with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network apparently has not much luck (in fact, now it would be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market which led to a considerable fall in prices, which was subsequently also borne by conventional operators.
Yet even before the emergence of such troublemakers as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those we hear today were being heard in Britain.
It has become apparent that there is still room for such operators and that they can be very successful.
We don't have to look far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
The Mobilking is also backed by the Penta financial group, which owns, among others, the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of constructing, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators are promoted as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which are often counterbalanced by a limited range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least twice the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, targeting an unusual target group can also be a good advertising strategy.
This operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust", says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work in our country as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický is doubtful: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
The Commission has also proposed that the European Parliament should be consulted on the proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment.
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say the mobile operators
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is to be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czechia the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area", said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were in any case not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not been hiding its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator for quite some time.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in the negotiations", says the group's spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be bright.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps welcome the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is a place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific in comparison with other markets.
At the moment, no one with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us", Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefonika O2 said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered for the moment viable and bilaterally advantageous projects that could serve as a basis".
She added: "It is virtually unlikely that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should have a concrete agreement now".
Vodafone is instead focusing on fulfilling the requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet".
The responsible authorities: in step with the operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
So what's the point in facilitating the arrival of such a competitor?
The operators are able to work together like thieves in a fair, as is also shown by the chicanes that accompanied the creation of the U:fon.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, when the U:fon was created, was the one exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is ready to be used as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: 'Competition in the mobile market has also been recently increased by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would place high demands on it, and especially on its services".
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The latter is the exclusive property of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
The latter took the typical position on this problem.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties was not sufficiently interesting for traditional operators", said Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS external relations department in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not be surprising on the part of representatives of operators.
But such a statement from an office whose duty is to represent the interests of consumers and also to ensure that no one takes advantage of his position on the market is beyond confusing.
This is all the more true when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside the EU, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decline in the prices of mobile telephone services".
However, pressing for fair market functioning and lower prices does not seem to be in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which arises from their reactions.
The question naturally arises whether this is really a coincidence.
Similarly, the fact that the price of petrol is exactly the same at all petrol stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
'The Office has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore no corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even in the telecommunications regulator", Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many points of disagreement.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators holds a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest that the creation of a virtual operator requires the consent of the network operator on a case-by-case basis.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
It is therefore necessarily playing a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
Even without accepting this argument, it should at least be of concern to ÚOHS that three mobile operators are apparently acting in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in their negotiations with all operators.
The blame shifting to the ČTÚ is a fairly common communications ploy, by which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already seen this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in extending the ČTÚ's powers in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must be well aware of this, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo-operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies which publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, this refers to firms that deal with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are usually only available to selected persons.
The magic trick is that the company presents itself to the operator as a conventional business customer, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you are saying happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would look into and that could lead to a breakdown of the collaboration with the company in question", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is unlikely that the heads of mobile operators have not been informed of such activity.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator is opposed to such a procedure.
The activities of these firms bring them substantial profits and, at the same time, unlike the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
Furthermore, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot have full access to it, as ordinary customers of mobile operators do".
And this is precisely what should seem strange about ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another question at ÚOHS.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the operators' explanations, they say they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we're not the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable reduction in the price of services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the traditional operators made some or all efforts to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, not in the interests of the mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Both by formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually succeeded in creating a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory agencies treat this issue like a hot potato that you throw away by passing it on to a nearby target.
We cannot, from our experience, get rid of the impression that confusing their skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw the handle after the hammer.
If the behind-the-scenes news is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our country, the Czech mobile market may be back on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS can hardly remain unmoved in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On the occasion of Czech National Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on Sunday solemnly released the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was re-recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with male or female solo singing, a choral interpretation and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The anthem was arranged by Jeremáš Otakar and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had already entrusted to the Czech public radio, he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to ensure that both singers and the choir had a good diction, so that the words were understood and they sang simultaneously", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first heard in 1834 on the stages of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of the Savers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
