The public transport (MHD) in Prague will introduce the chip in their ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will go down in the history of Pražský Dopravní podnik (Prague Transport Agency) as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, with an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it is available to approximately one hundred thousand Opencard holders.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day voucher (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency) located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
As of yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy the coupons online on the Dopravní podnik website: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people took advantage of the morning service.
Those who start using the online store can forget about the ticket counters in the subway stations, where they have to wait impatiently in long queues for paper tickets.
They will buy their voucher online and it will be saved on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these contact points, there is a ticket office with trained staff, who will help the customers with the online purchase and, in addition, will record the coupon they have purchased on their card", says the project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the lobby of several metro stations.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of the ticket composting machines, and passengers may have already noticed them at Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
A machine will check the coupon instead of the driver
The automata that will be operational from tomorrow are easy to use.
Just insert the Opencard chip and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surroundings of the city.
The main routes are the suburban trains and buses 300 to 499, which are used mainly by the inhabitants of the central Bohemian municipalities to reach the capital.
"In the trains integrated into Pražská integrovaná doprava (Prague integrated transport), the controllers are equipped with card readers, with which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of the coupons", explained ticket controller Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which designs the timetables of Prague public transport.
The suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver's cash register.
When boarding, it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard in the indicated place on the side of the ticket office.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take the suburban buses and will not remember the expiry date of their voucher, can rejoin the vending machines, originally used to save the coupons on the card.
This is where the information on the validity of the document will be displayed on the screen of the device.
The Sudetenlanders were calling for a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the Sudetenland demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This is stated in a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (South Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945 groups of Sudeten Germans were allegedly addressing the President of the USA with such a desire.
This is partly due to a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
The letter from the Germans of Český Krumlov asks the US President not to allow the "šumavská župa" (forest region in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops are coming to the German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of the Šumava", reads.
Since the alleged promise of a Czech-Czechoslovak alliance - and the Czech national character - is only brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter urge the American president to take the protectorate of Šumava into his own hands once and for all.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state that is foreign to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has done nothing to contribute to the Allied victory without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants", the letter reads.
The alleged reason the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of the vengeful desire of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would have to organise, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US, or live under the patronage of the US.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of postwar history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it does illustrate the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans must have at least foreseen the question of their expulsion from the republic, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would secure some sort of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others thought they would just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who was born in České Budějovice.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, enlisted in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the British and placed in the Holstein region's prison camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to learn Czech.
"They thought that once they returned home, Czech would be useful", Chalupa says.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, as a result of the Beneš Decrees, they would be expelled from the republic.
You're not thinking - you're paying!
A campaign of emotions will attack the drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transportation intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of Minister Aleš Řebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This 150 million campaign will be shown on television, radio, film, on the Internet, and in leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving too fast and drinking.
But also remind them to put on their seat belts before they start.
It is intended above all to affect the conscience of young drivers, motorists, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the ads?
Especially personal stories that will attack the emotions.
The campaign's "bloody" slogan is also a testimony to this:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a pool of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay".
It's a symbol that one can pay for one moment of inattention with one's life.
The ads will haunt viewers until 2010.
The Ministry has drawn inspiration from similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where pictures of the victims of accidents are commonly seen.
He believes that this will lead to a reduction in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the agency Euro RSCG.
The sugar and whip strategy against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they turn on a red light.
A whip is a threat of a fine or an accident.
Drivers need to be reminded of the risks", says Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
The psychologist believes that this is why we need information campaigns in the press, and particularly negative publicity.
He said that the warning signs for drivers are already less effective.
"When a static sign is installed that warns of danger, it will probably blend into the environment quickly and drivers will not notice it", says Kořán.
