Questions arising after the accident: Are the stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is forbidden
In the wake of the tragic bus accident of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move around inside the bus during the journey.
"If the law is to be strictly and formally observed, the activity of a flight attendant is contrary to the law on road traffic", said Karel Hanzelka, a spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old flight attendant was killed, was apparently caused by a truck driver who crossed the bus.
The girl was unfortunately sitting next to the driver in the most dangerous seat in the vehicle, although she had two other seats available to her.
The bus may crash or even brake abruptly, even when the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
The important thing is whether the coach is equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing-up equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance buses run by Student Agency do not have standing seats, which was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company's director Radim Jančura.
"This is an issue we have dealt with with the Ministry and, at first, it forbids any movement of passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got that passengers can go to the toilet during the journey provided they have their own seat", he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no single legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescriptions deal with this role.
Nor does any legal requirement prevent the carrier from offering services.
The road transport law only defines the term 'recipient of a vehicle' and does not define his rights and duties", adds spokesman Hanzelka with more ambiguity.
Josef Pokorný, the director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
"It all depends on whether the bus has in its homologation the permission to offer standing places.
It's all in there", he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing seats and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing seats and a higher allowed speed and long-distance buses without standing seats with the highest allowed maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like in the airplane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, a BESIP (Road Traffic Safety) transport safety expert, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In normal traffic there is no danger, and the situation can be compared to that of the airline.
There, too, it is not certain when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant may hit her head".
"If the bus had brake abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously apply.
The same way you would in a city bus or a streetcar.
The carrier must manage the safety of the stewards by internal prescriptions", he said, adding that the problem was not solved from the point of view of the law.
Jančura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus operator to offer steward services.
He's hired 200 of them.
Even after that accident, the manager doesn't consider their job to be a risky job.
"But as soon as I feel it is a risky job, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on boarding.
It would also reduce costs", he said.
The reason given by the director of Asiana Alexeï Litvine for the absence of stewards in his vehicles is concern for safety, which provides, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses. We've been against it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident", he told Týden.cz a year ago.
A great tragedy has come
A young hostess from the Plzeň region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop lane without using a flashing light and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid him by means of a sudden manoeuvre, but he brushed him on his right side.
Jančura denies that the two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards were sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked".
The company is planning to file a complaint against the truck driver.
As for compensation for the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the court's decision, but as for financial compensation, it also relies on the perpetrator.
A change in the law?
Out of sight
An amendment to the law, which has been under development for over a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide more details about the travel of stewards on board the coach.
"Now, it has not come to any conclusion on this point.
In fact, it is not very interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of mobile phones while driving", says expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers", concludes the spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the safety control of buses is under the authority of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of Düsseldorfs are often placed in Frankfurt.
The letter from the WestLB board of directors to the employees of the company was full of big words.
The letter published on Monday said that the merger of the Düsseldorf financial institution with Deka-Bank in Frankfurt could create "the central financial market institution of the Sparkasse financial group".
WestLB would provide a 'competence block' with a durable productivity in such a case.
In sum, such a relationship could be the decisive trigger for further concentrations in the Länder's banking sector.
This is what it looks like when a board of directors wants to prove its ability to act in difficult times.
Because WestLB, wounded, is still under a lot of pressure.
It is not only the European Commission but also the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority that has, only recently, made it clear to the government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time was running out in the search for a future solution.
However, there has been talk for some time - also from Frankfurt - of some form of relationship between Deka Bank, which knows the customers of the Sparkasse through their investment funds, and WestLB.
It is true that the head of Deta-Bank, Franz Waas, stated at the time of the presentation of the figures for the half-year at the end of August that he saw no point in the merger of the Mainzer Landstrasse bank with a Land bank, either Helaba or WestLB.
However, the board of directors of Deka, each of which is supported half by the Länder banks and savings bank groups, has instructed the management committee to conduct talks with WestLB with a view to joint business activities.
This could then be the flow of the financial market, or parts thereof.
The talks are only just beginning, however, the financial centre says.
It is not the first time that Deta-Bank, which, with its 3000 employees, is one of the largest employers in Frankfurt's financial centre, has been involved in the consolidation of the savings bank sector.
In 2003 it was for a while believed that Deta-Bank might merge with the Rhineland-Palatinate Land Bank and Halbab.
But nothing has come out of this triune bouquet.
The plans had just been made public that the government of the Land of Hesse had spoken out against any participation of the Hellaba in them.
Later, the other two houses also did not join.
The Bank of the Land of Rhineland Palatinate was instead attached to the Bank of the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there were always new negotiations on the merger of Deka-Bank with Länder banks.
Finally, however, Günther Merl, Chairman of the Board of Directors of Hellaba, had spoken out against any commercial merger strategy with his bank.
Regardless, there seems to be a widespread feeling that the consolidation of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the election to the Landtag of Bavaria has taken place, a union of BayernLB with the Landbank of Baden-Württemberg could be realized first and foremost.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure to force new mergers were to increase, potential partners would gradually escape him.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it had so far withstood the crisis better than the banks in Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringe savings and transfer bank group, which holds 85% of Helaba's capital, however, closed down the merger with WestLB at the beginning of the year.
The NordLB would be the best option.
Such geostrategic considerations, however, reflect only one aspect.
Another aspect is how the different business models of each of these banks can be combined.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question of which business model should ensure the future capacity of the Länder banks had not yet been resolved by the German savings and credit union group.
In the long run, a cutting of the WestLB could take place, a cutting which is obviously not desired here.
This is also what the letter from the existing management committee is about: in any case, it would be a 'global solution' for the establishment.
How all this will be put together with the merger of some entities with Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
