Sleepless nights for the shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word 'relatively' and that he was able to slip that the German banking sector would not be spared by the movements of the crisis.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed on the DAX, obtains a loan of one billion from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to the amount of 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the portion of the loan it would be entitled to.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, the subsidiary Depfa is bearing the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself on a very short-term basis for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible due to the lack of confidence in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to EUR 2,37 million, and the equity ratio had also fallen slightly from 1,6 to 1,45 percent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions were zero points below the same period in the previous year, while profits from the allocation of debt securities and from the cancellation of provisions in credit operations were down by more than 70% to EUR 5 million.
It was only thanks to the substantial profits from the reimbursement of the downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the interest reimbursement according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the Konzern companies that the profit deficit of around 16 per cent proved to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had at first speculated poorly on industrial real estate loans, which were then subsidiaries of Aareal Bank.
Because conventional public financing was not sufficiently profitable, Depfa then became more intensely involved in infrastructure projects and in financing joint projects between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
The value of the subsidiary is subject to depreciation by Hypo Real Estate, which should have a material effect on the calculation of the group's profits and losses, which is still quite vague.
The point is, the dividends have been cut.
By 2007, they had already been cut to two thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has, since the purchase of Depfa, been a highly important investor in the State and in infrastructure.
It is stronger than other institutions that rely on refinancing on the interbank market, as it does not have any customer deposits.
With the collapse of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks has again increased considerably, as banks have accumulated liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing facility annually for a portion - approximately EUR 50 billion - of all Depfa loans.
According to a Hypo Real Estate press release, the group's financing needs are covered by medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets which are largely out of order at the moment.
Other sources say the refinancing will be secured by the funds until the end of 2009.
However, HRE's Chairman of the Board Georg Funke explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to the financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (Bafin) assume that the capacity of the Hypo Real Group on the market is now assured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope.
However, given the dynamics and the unpredictability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that the full range of financing should be used.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still on the verge of insolvency late Sunday evening, this at least temporary rescue will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price plunged 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While the main debt has barely moved, the price of the secondary loans has been falling.
The investment funds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and those with a lifespan of more than 2009 are the most affected.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank, which previously appeared to be an alternative speculative investment, now have to be regarded as depending on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself which brought the crisis into the establishment by the purchase of Depfa Bank.
As long as the issuers, governments and less affected commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that the leakage will be absorbed over time.
Or what no one dares to hope for at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But with renewed talk of partial nationalisation, the probability that security was approaching has now become a mere hope.
This should save sleepless nights for long-term creditors in particular over the decision whether to part with their liabilities.
Short-term investors can still use what they have written off to carry forward losses for the next few years on the next capital gains tax automatically levied.
