Rats have feelings too
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have sensations too.
But how can we be sure that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of articles that answer the question "What do you think is true without having any proof?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove it until now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and we approach the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into terrain that is difficult to do because the hardware does not match.
When faced with danger, a rat does what many other animals do: it either feigns death, runs away or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists infer a similar subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in it.
Two aspects of the brain's structure make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience to that of animals.
One aspect is that circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in executive and executive functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other creatures.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and to make decisions, it's reasonable to assume that human beings are even different from other primates.
Another significant feature could be the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In that case, we could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness were not to be dependent on language, it would surely be influenced by it, so that animal consciousness, however it is produced, would probably be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what the conscience of other animals may be like.
If this internal and subjective cannot be measured or, because of this particular hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then we have big problems observing it.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
You could look at the processes of consciousness in animals without looking at the content, and that's exactly what happened in studies of short-term memory in primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which was followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, the focus is more on the neural correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of the prefrontal cortex in making the visualization.
But what does this mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a conscious brain of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its suites, such as the body's reactions) takes over the vivid memory.
As we observe, emotions are closely linked to the cortex regions that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our fickle nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute to others than to ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the cortical cortex and brainstem regions of body sensation, just as Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network hasn't changed much in the course of human evolution, it could very well be involved in cross-sensitivity of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot dispute this, but I believe it to be unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and in rats is probably also felt as fear in both cases: how could we verify whether rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave in a similar way?
