In a city of part, the pride and trials of black life
Hidden in the development of its vast park, a few miles from sunny, bright and giant Orlando, lies a quiet little town where pride and the complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first all-black town to be incorporated, childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, that description she gave in 1935 is not so easy to do today". "The town of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of goyaves, two schools and no jail".
It has now become a city of pilgrimage
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora Festival in Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in many ways, the town she describes - which has become a tourist destination thanks to its inclusion in the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project's Florida tourist guide - is still a place of its own.
It is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston said that the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing us so little, doesn't know what he's missing".
Even though this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has also called for an open dialogue on the topic of race, many here remain cautious of the foreigners' gaze.
"We are very careful about how we tell the story", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and the town's oldest parishioner.
"it must be in accordance with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and combat.
It represents both a historic model of black power and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a focal point but also an example of black Southern rural culture - sometimes despised, sometimes acclaimed - that recalls the birth of American slavery.
Which would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
Interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through such heartfelt, dialect-filled books as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide transformed this town, located just off of Route 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten heart of Florida, culminating in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a big box in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
"Across the road on the left", she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its gardens and those well-maintained playgrounds which Howard Miller has always cared for, although he can hardly read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that "Lee Glenn" sells all kinds of drinks and anything that passersby can use.
So, in just over a hundred words, Hurston associates Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn't really a portrait that everybody liked.
Zora described the reality well", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the young Johnson girls whom Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston used to arrive in town unannounced, in a big Chevrolet, a cigarette in his mouth and wearing pants here, where even today, we pride ourselves on traditional attire.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed at her.
"people were always happy to see Zora" he said.
But he added, rocking in his chair from the backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was likely baptized, that "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a common grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she lived.
In Eatonville, there's no big commemorations, no plaque for the general public to see.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered to the world", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A turning point came in the 1980's.
Orange County public officials wanted to bring a five-lane highway into the city, to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's two-lane main street.
Orlando's development has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made as Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among so many other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the dispute over race mixing led to hatred at the gates of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white kids would come in and throw oranges or things at people sitting on the side", said Mr. Franklin.
"a lady has even passed away".
They threw a watermelon from their car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's application for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorifying my race".
Residents now claim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some respects, has diluted Eatonville's cohesion and weakened young people's confidence.
"Black children used to be kissed - I remember that well - we used to kiss our master in the morning, and in the evening too", said N.Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter and the executive director of the Eatonville Community Safety Group, a nonprofit.
This continued, she said, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white - I mean there's a cultural dividing line here", Ms Nathiri said.
Civil rights, by the way, has helped to create space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, such as herself, armed with a joyful self-confidence and lines of conduct such as, "How can they deny themselves the pleasure of my company!"
It's beyond me".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston's unmarked grave and began to struggle to revive his reputation.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed best-selling biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway reintroduced her to the American canon.
The highway project came at just the right moment when Eatonville's most famous girl had found her attraction.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community began to hold a Hurston Festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of this highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival's opening two years later, and many return in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the county rejected the highway proposal.
"The five-lane highway fiasco, extremely fast, a real civic pride", said Ms. Nathiri.
Miss Boyd summed it up by saying that "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who's been attending our church since 1993, started coming in large numbers, and residents were starting to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been a historic district since 1998.
A single-theme library (of course named Hurston) opened in 2006 on a beautiful, renovated Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a summer rainy day, as small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Now we have 90 percent black people)
Foreigners who come to learn about Eatonville's history, its reason for being, are still treated with caution.
