"I photograph the master off stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes that would make you feel bad.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to achieve the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On one side is the artist.
The other, the person.
Separate but in the privacy of those moments unknown to the public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen looks of artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer combines in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the program of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which grows every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of the personality of these artists, you don't take pictures on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the flamenco stars' personality moments with my camera".
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer started in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, resemble classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dancing or the singing itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has developed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment longer or shorter.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or who leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 of the Rue de la Mata (a street parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16th.
