The Ministry of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcoholism, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting in a drunken state, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered as a pilot project that will last for a year.
Its aim is to reintegrate the driver by offering him courses in road rehabilitation.
The Minister of State for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation will be involved in this initiative.
Statistics show that between 30 and 75 percent of all drivers arrested for drunk driving more than once take their car back.
The Alcohol Lock would prevent this since it is a system plugged into the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe first; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than the permitted one.
The cost is over 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of offences in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 lives every year.
This measure is based on administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done through ordinary channels, but reform through criminal channels requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to the Council, which is the body responsible for the implementation of the directive.
