Talking in your sleep
Some children talk in the night.
I'm not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk in their sleep.
It may surprise you the first time it happens, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called somniloquia.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking in the night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitation.
It's an understudied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet, small voice, with isolated words, whispers or with shouting, crying, long speeches...
If sleepwalking becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to see if there is a problem that is causing much anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a mild disorder, so there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What we can do is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
So look for games that are not violent, and avoid TV programs that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will help the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepiness starts to appear, try to stay calm.
Remember, they are harmless to the child and the next day he will have no memory of what happened.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's no use, because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests so.
Remember, if he shows signs of severe anxiety repeatedly, it is advisable to consult a doctor or to find out what is causing the child so much anxiety.
If you understand what he is saying (which is unusual), do not be tempted to ask questions to get information.
You'll get nothing, because in sleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Also, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and draw conclusions from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to learn his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
It causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, this is not a bad thing, it's just an episode that lasts a few minutes.
