Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
The President of the Republic decided to go to the port of Guilvinec, in Finistère, on Tuesday morning to meet their representatives.
The latter promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with practical proposals".
The presidential visit coincides with a general assembly of the "crisis committee" set up by Breton fishermen to obtain measures to deal with the soaring price of diesel fuel, which has reached a record high of more than 1.14 euros per litre on average.
According to the spokesman for the Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them the solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of seamen".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected to stand firm by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they carried out snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing traffic jams of almost 10 km.
The Quiberon marina was also blocked, but the connections to Belle-île were not stopped.
A sealing dam was put in place on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors have already shown their determination by burning tires and paddles in front of the fuel depots in the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic and Channel sides, such as the Sands d'Olonne in Vendée, where the trawlers were docked, and the Havre, where some 20 boats blocked the movements of commercial vessels.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantique, have stopped the blockade of the important Total refinery in Donges.
The people of Boulogne-sur-Mer have decided to wait for the meeting of Wednesday at the ministry to decide on possible actions.
The "crisis committee" at Guilvinec must decide on Tuesday what action to take against the movement and whether to attend the meeting scheduled for the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials from the National Fisheries Committee, which did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not give up anything" and "do not want to move to Paris", announced for example Liliane Cariou, the president of the fisheries committee of Lorient.
The professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per litre but they believe that the threshold of profitability of a boat is only reached with a diesel fuel of less than 0.30 euro per litre.
