The interview - blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood donors in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the trust of the public who had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood supply operated by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service was contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In view of this tragedy and the public outcry, the Government of Canada in February 1994 instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Justice Krever was delayed in presenting his report, some provinces then formed a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Company to supply all the other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38 per cent of people had confidence in the blood system in Québec", recalls Dr Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained the public's trust", she said, before proudly stating that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
From its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, Europe was witnessing the emergence of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has been prevalent since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
The main recommendation of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures should be introduced.
In April 1999, blood was thus refused to those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But in recent years it has been proved beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This incident showed us that the precautionary principle was a good one".
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV test technique was introduced: the nucleic acid test (NAT), which detects the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of donors, rather than the antibody against the virus, which was the basis of the tests used until then.
The TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends from the time the person is infected to the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, she says.
We were able to reduce that to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may be infected without being aware of it and thus not be detected.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one person in every 12 million is at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before anyone can be infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before there is a case of HIV transmission from a blood product.
I believe that today people can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing blood transfusions to restore their health", says the CEO of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island. Like the West Nile virus, it is transmitted by blood from an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr Décary, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for an adequate supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be refilled in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which comprises on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation".
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria may still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors must be renewed as they grow older and are no longer able to donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even more difficult to stop them from donating blood and to encourage them to become regular donors.
"The rush of life today is such that we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and are planning to collect more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
