The Prime Minister does not rule out calling elections before the end of the year
As soon as the Liberal Party's general council ended, Jean Charest went to Jean-Talon, Quebec, yesterday, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected in today's by-election.
"Pushing back the limits of our last great northern frontier" was the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in the main lines at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec in Lévis yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was a sort of image mill.
Loops of spectacular images of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec as seen by Google Maps, maps, and so on were shown on three huge screens.
Big money, like in an election.
In a press conference, the Prime Minister refused to rule out that he would call the elections this autumn, even though he pointed out that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes a labour force agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in recent speeches by the Prime Minister, the opening of the North - the Northern Territory at the 49th parallel - had never been presented before.
The Prime Minister, however, merely explained why the North was "a jewel with immense potential", but did not give a timetable, investment amounts, or precise priorities for future projects.
At most, there are a few avenues of what could be developed further: hydroelectricity, forestry, but especially the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds", according to Mr. Charest's list.
This territory twice the size of France is our home, it's in Quebec.
It's not just in our house, it's in us", he insisted, as if to make clear that he was calling for a national founding myth.
He said that Quebec had built up a lot in its relationship with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, the James Bay.
"This is ours, this is our future", he added, after taking a theatrical pause to contemplate the huge map behind him.
The North, 70 per cent of Quebec territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the premier said at the press briefing.
"It is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and when the opportunity arises, I reiterate this position on behalf of the government", he said.
The European Union is also working to ensure that the EU's fishing fleet is able to compete with the world's fishing fleet.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister feels that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the people who live in the land, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially the young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pequist MP for Ungava), have already started consultations with some 30 communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has a prominent place, started work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment where "we will give each other a common vision".
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
