Free thought - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 issue, The Debtor published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six million defamation suit against three authors and a small publishing house with no money in order to start a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in cases of libel prosecution, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely overlooked by Mr Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to take a position contrary to his own.
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and to fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to bankrupt the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was to the public that she should have presented her version of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are normally held through the exchange of ideas and not by the use of clubs.
The mine had to open its books and files and start a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and has been rebuffing petitions and letters in support of Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both call for a "public" debate and disregard the opinions of that same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word only refers to the highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that's a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even the detractors have a say.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public who support Black Canada's authors and publishers do so primarily because they reject the brutal way the mine is run.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a lawsuit-bail (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a notice to the authors of Black Canada telling them to stop using this term ...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surrealist rhetoric, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic inquiry and the pursuit of truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in its entirety, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that are unpleasant to the rich corporations of this world in a country like Canada, under the threat of repeated prosecutions, who will do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long known how to handle debate and disagreement and resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's out-of-bounds lawsuit makes it clear that, contrary to its claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to academia, as well as to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
