The new version of the $700 billion plan to contain the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides for: better control by elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to control the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican negotiator Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress toward a deal that will be effective in the markets", said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done in a way that shielded the real economy and ordinary Americans from the crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"This is the bottom line: if we don't do this, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense", said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had been sped up in the last few hours over fears of the effect of a further failure on investor sentiment.
The deadline we agreed on was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates for the US presidency, who were late to join the negotiations, were rather favourable to the agreement, but expressed their dissatisfaction that it had to come to this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has claimed credit for adding provisions to the agreement, including one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and one on the salaries of executives of businesses bailed out by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of irresponsibility, there is no room for complacency.
But these measures are necessary", he said on US television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
"The big lines I read [showed] that this is something that we're all going to have to digest and we're going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan is to use taxpayers' money to buy back the bad, unsafe and unsellable assets of American financial institutions.
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and the liquidation of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who threw the first draft of the agreement last week.
We think we've gotten out of this deadlock since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of troubled companies should only be insured by the government, rather than bought.
To round off the corners for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stating that if the government were to take losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for a first instalment of 250 billion, with a further 100 billion to be paid if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion would have to be approved by another vote in Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will get shares in the bailed-out companies that will pay dividends if it makes a profit and that it can sell back when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will be able to delay foreclosure proceedings concerning housing attached to the mortgages covered by this plan, and to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to a vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be approved.
Yesterday, there were still voices against the bill, both Republican and Democratic.
"Obviously, Washington is not listening to you", said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is about taking advantage of taxpayers".
The leader of a small congressional group dubbed the "skeptics caucus", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to say: we ask the Congress not to rush and to consider carefully the way forward", he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe was once again witnessing the global nature of the crisis.
Following an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up acquiring its bankrupt rival since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the subprime mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the 10 largest insurers.
'This is not money wasted,' said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, we get back a vote in the bank and influence.
This is something that savers and households are enjoying now that times are uncertain".
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government seemed to be on its way to nationalizing another bank that had been battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over 41 billion (US$ 75.5 billion) in mortgage loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would be buying the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government would have to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of an iconic and committed
Her blue-eyed beauty was her strong suit for a long time, some might say her weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the fountain will also have kept him away from the power register that breeds true sacred monsters.
But what a great distance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last remaining icons of the golden age of American cinema.
Less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and for whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on screen, more careful in his playing, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the brilliance of dramatic conventions.
Interbreeding often produces beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots will emerge one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
No ego, the ultimate in quality.
Because in him was projected a whole country in love with the self-made man, the combatant of the Pacific War, wounded in combat, who in the early 1950s studied drama at Yale then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, on television, soon in cinema.
This same civil rights activist was also the race car driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, dubbed a sex symbol, though he was part of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The shadows of this secret, discreet, committed, allergic to the sparkles of show business, whose enigma has not been fully deciphered, also disappear with him.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman has sent a shiver through movie audiences this weekend as his iconic roles collide on the silver screen of remembrance.
Over half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual flux is marching through it.
The cowboy charm of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) is brought back to mind, as the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Tennessee Williams' 1958 adaptation of The Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.
Closer to Us (1990), it is about his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all its promises.
So many Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, the delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable character in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, reprised after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic villain in the brilliant The Sting, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
A bitter and vindictive billiard player in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he reprised the character on his return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar in 1987 out of nine nominations.
That face through the ages, that was him.
It's him again.
The ages are jostling through its course.
Young people know him best through the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of a less orthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
With a final role as the godfather of the Irish mob in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the circle was closed.
Unlike many movie legends who left the business early enough, Newman would remain in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its gold, its whims and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humour, "as a living challenge to the underplaying judging his performances too supported.
The profession has not always been easy for the handsome Paul Newman, whose roles have long been a no-brainer.
He played the young leaders less often than the marginals: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the drift and revolt.
As a filmmaker, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true, unassuming sensibility.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the leading role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He lost his son Scott to an overdose and dedicated his film Harry and Son in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the tributes that poured down on Newman yesterday, his good friend and former fellow soldier Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very sadly: "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the late actor.
Beyond his legendary career, a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a critic of the Hollywood excesses, is also gone.
Many have seen the beetle sitting on sauces, sauces, biscuits, and other food, judging the process to be rather bad-tasting, though initially profitable.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Difficulty.
Newman, instead of sitting on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left a letter to his five daughters that included these words: "From the beginning to the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be there".
And it's been a privilege for us to have followed the journey of such a lucid and generous American artist.
A model citizen, in short.
What could Zuschlag &amp; Company have made in their factory of invoices ?
The hearings on the ongoing criminal case against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, permanently and regularly, having caused particularly significant damage.
According to the prosecution, the money from the grants was being spent for personal use, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and the municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went to the cash registers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and to the pockets of certain individuals.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money for the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices for costs, behind which no real service was provided and thus the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large proportion of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
The names of companies that were to appear on the invoices were decided, among others, during the tours in the province of the North of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the witness's statement, he was supposed to be tracking down guesthouses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the basis of which they prepared the other invoices that they would submit, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
In a "scouting tour", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided food for a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy the place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the bill drawn up on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which later became known as Egypt's Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors in form and substance.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj actually had only three rooms and could accommodate up to ten people, but the bill mentioned 130 guests.
The fact that the applicant had not been informed of the existence of the undertaking, and that the Commission had not been informed of the fact that the undertaking had been registered, does not mean that the Commission had not been informed of the existence of the undertaking.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew right away that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and tax number were wrongly placed on the stamp".
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people stayed there, also did not fit, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
And the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time".
The eager invoice-issuers also did not inquire about the Budapest travel agencies, which were part of their choice, but only arranged trips abroad, and so they naively indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
In addition, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, whereas services relating to travel activities, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up on behalf of the Révfülöp Hotel at the request of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services did not bear VAT of 25%, as stated, but VAT of 15%.
The investigation of the public prosecutor revealed that the 'issuers' also made mistakes in mentioning the transport of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it was also for formal defects, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued on behalf of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and of Biztos Pont were found to be false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó Sporting Stage, both of which deny that they are the authors of the invoices issued in their name.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time when (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their home.
Invoices made intentionally
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, has drawn up an invoice to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért foundation, for the sum of HUF four million.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was made to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation, cooperated with the Zuschlags and in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but no services were actually provided.
There was no financial movement either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but the agencies avoided mentioning this in their accounts.
The next category of invoicing companies is those directly related to the defendants.
The administrative deputy of the general manager of the company Delta Trió Kft. dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he was not to be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and de Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their counter value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies were operating, which the accused explained by the fact that they were not receiving work.
He nevertheless made use of these companies, since at the request of Mr Zsolt Szente, the co-accused and draftsman of the foundation acts of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, in the name of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave to the agencies a total of 15 invoices issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, with a value of HUF 14,2 million.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices and the VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices which were used in the context of the grant application of Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted an application for a grant to the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this subsidy for the amount of two HUF 500 000 but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to TMA.
In fact, these are the invoices that were found during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will describe the method of manufacturing the invoices, as they had already done before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be if the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decided to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or whether, possibly, the socialists would have reached an agreement that in return for the reimbursement of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would be the sole bearer of the burden.
Today, the latter is probably annoyed, since the requests for his placement under house arrest, on the basis of a lighter detention conditions, are continuously falling on deaf ears.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of irreparable economic crimes, are walking around freely or at least waiting in their own homes for the end of the proceedings.
The psychology of over-bid: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overvalue the merchandise.
Neuroscientists and economists at the City University of New York have succeeded in uncovering the neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings don't want to be left out of this kind of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that's why they're even willing to pay a price that's too high.
This research has attempted to construct a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while the researchers analyzed the active brain regions of the experimental subjects using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) technique.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction, one key element of which is the overbid of a third, the whole underneath the brain stem, called the striatum, would be set in motion intensely when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Hence, the researchers believe that the reason for the price increase is the flight of the striatum's violent reaction.
In support of their theories, the economists in this group of researchers carried out analyses of financial surveillance.
In these, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the real value of the product in question, and they carried out their bet.
Another group was promised that if they won the game, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
Whereas the third group got this $15 before the auction, but the members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is actually that the emphasis in the one was on winning, while in the other, on failing.
In proof of the neurologists' hypothesis, the "against failure" team members were willing to bet higher than the control and "for victory" teams.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Each of them explained the phenomena observed at auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the risk-taking.
It was only the techniques of neurological imaging that helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories and now lead to a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor at the New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is listed as the leading cause of death.
An estimated 100,000 people in Hungary are infected with hepatitis, but only 7,000 are receiving treatment because they often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is a general name for infections of the liver caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms, such as inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the pathogens and the underlying diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, are spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated food, usually accompanied by a general bad state of health, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then, visible yellowing develops on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stools become lighter, and the urine becomes darker in color.
Around the world, a million people die every year from the most serious forms of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people with the disease do not know they have the virus because the pathogenic gene silently destroys the liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 to 30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as is regular screening.
The contamination rate is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
Currently, an estimated 200 million people worldwide are chronically infected with hepatitis C.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory testing, it is advisable to consult the treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating the risk of contagion and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral liver cirrhosis, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does believing in God make you feel less pain ?
According to the results of a recent study, religious belief is a kind of painkiller, which has already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph reported that researchers at Oxford University had conducted an interesting experiment to determine how belief in God could influence the human tolerance of pain.
In this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electric shocks as each of them looked at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the suffering.
It was also discovered that by using a technique of palpation of the human brain, Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments involving academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment is conducted in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and distributing the electric shocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the experiment participants to look at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a sort of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not unlike the first, was based on its calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four successive sessions, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that seeing the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", "cared for", and "calmed down, and peace came over them".
When they saw the religious painting, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was involved in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, among atheists, provided the appropriate image is found.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After these excellent results, the only question left is what would be the effect on the regulation of the subjects' pain if we showed the faithful a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would a better quality Virgin Mary be more effective?
You are what you reveal about yourself
On its tenth anniversary, Google says it can be found in the back of people's pockets as well as the sky above their heads - where they spent their holidays, what experts they consulted and what their interests are.
But that's not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the most influential people in society.
As for the skeptics drawing a parallel with Orwell's vision of horror, they are missing the essence of the Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to collect even more information about its users, which is necessary for the founders of Google to meet their original goal which was: "Let's collect all the world's information in one system!".
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of global switching work, they are still just at the beginning of their goals to be able to process all the information.
To the question: what will be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What job would be best for me?". However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, which is simple at first glance, once they know enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer that initiated the search and the pages subsequently consulted by the interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they have searched for, what they have clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long run, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous declarations and our stored preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what I do? users ask, worried about Google's monopoly on information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can cause fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can cause a backlash among Internet users.
It is a confirmed fact, however, that the search terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most notable recent example is the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google passed information it had collected from the public page called Orkut to the Brazilian government, allowing for identification.
Internet users concerned about human rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May when Google, in a showdown with the Electronic Legal Defense Fund, proved its right in court against the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will not be able to be obliged by any constitutional provision to disclose information on the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won over the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier, but ultimately failed to obtain the private user search lists, or the entire list of websites and keywords for the past two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is being reprimanded by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their privacy and private sphere is being affected when they start using Google services, and therefore they attack them in the spirit of revolt against multinational corporations that pride themselves on their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savages" of computer enthusiasts, activists and enthusiasts appearing in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the "technology corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, which is being labeled as the world invader because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification codes, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the program package, continually refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, compared to the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very clearly the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what the Web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, is pulling behind it.
The Web 2.0 is really about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind us, and using the communication channels that are available to us, and while the dimensions of these channels change one by one, the essence remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can have a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and they can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing their music habits. Then they can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep blogs, in which their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa appear automatically.
While there are many examples, such as the girlfriend who can easily understand the morning photos taken by the circle of mutual friends with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or the company that fired one of its employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, one thing is certain: the term privacy is totally to reconsider these days.
Who lives an online life, is what he shows about himself, and that's how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's youth.
If you want to hide something, or at least try to circumvent Google's monopoly, you can (by starting with, for example, Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
Google's online services, from word processing to image processing to reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not tied to huge server parks and which do not bring together our best profile, which has existed to date.
The public is waiting, not really hiding from it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
