The Warsaw Stock Exchange makes a proposal to buy the Prague Stock Exchange
The Warsaw Stock Exchange offered two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech crowns, for the purchase of 100% of the Prague Stock Exchange's stock.
Ludwik Sobolewski, the chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed this proposal made by the Poles, despite the fact that the Czechs had previously excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for this exclusion is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is in the hands of the State.
99% of the shares are held by the Polish State which is seeking to divest itself of more than 60% of its shares within a few months of operation.
According to the Czech business daily E15, the Polish bid represents the highest bid that has been made so far for the purchase of the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the transatlantic Nasdaq, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Börse have made an offer so far.
Petr Koblic, the director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among the interested parties, the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the new owner the worst, and did not exclude the fact that this could lead to the disappearance of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague stock exchange is estimated by market experts at between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns.
On the basis of an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the shares would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance, with about 25 per cent of the shares, followed by the bank Ceská Sporitelna with 14.7 per cent and Tiger Holding Four S. a.r.l. with 13.5 per cent.
