The intelligent car mimics the flight of the drone
What better way to develop technology that can avoid an obstacle than to imitate an obstacle detector already in existence in nature?
Like the one with the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, buzzing bees have provided the strategic starting point for Nissan engineers to inspire how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C self-driving robotic system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee creates its own space, oval in shape, which in reality is very similar to our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and public relations technology department.
The bee's multifaceted eye plays a vital role, as it is able to see in all directions, up to an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, engineers have considered the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an evasive maneuver immediately.
The sensing of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, and then the mini-autobot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system that exists today, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not, the mini robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is considered inevitable for the time being.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must be done in a heartbeat.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the endless combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotational motion, acceleration and deceleration as manoeuvres available to the mini robot car.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, making them longer-lasting than the Lithium-ion version.
Andoh's view is that the most important thing is the intelligent, instinctive response, not the processing of data, much less the ability to store it.
This mechanism must only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It does not need to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, and in this way it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need gigabyte capacity or even megabyte capacity of memory.
This is the first step towards the design of an instantaneous avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be introduced in mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his way.
