The written version of the $700 billion bailout plan, designed to buy back the banks' bad loans, and to use them in multiple ways, is ready.
In the first round, half of that sum will be spent.
Reuters reports that in further debate that lasted until after midnight Saturday, East Coast time, congressional leaders agreed on the days-long controversy surrounding the $700 billion bailout.
"We have taken a serious step forward", said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the US House of Representatives, who said the only thing left to do was to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born of the plan, is supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, commenting on the outcome of the compromise, said the program would work and be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented.
The written version of the plan was released before the opening of Asian markets at 8pm local time in Washington on Sunday (i.e. 2am local time in Central Europe on Monday) but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock market.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill that will become the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, and then the Senate will decide its fate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The programme also differs from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion should be spent in one go, for the purchase of securities on dubious loans.
Now, the maximum amount that can be spent is half of the $700 billion, the first $250 billion of which will be released immediately after the bill is passed by Congress, probably on Monday, the first of which will go to the Secretary of the Treasury to buy bad loans from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the Federal Reserve Chairman will also participate.
The spending of the second half of the 700 billion depends on a new act of Congress.
Under the Act, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: it will be able to buy, at the same time, bad debt securities, mortgage securities and bad mortgages, as well as other types of 'toxic' debt.
The Ministry's officials stated that the purchases can be made through an auction or directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance scheme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that caused the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said that the law provides the tools necessary to allocate $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it be the large-scale redemption of bad loans, their insurance, or avoiding the risk of seeing the system collapse one or the other major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary measures to be ready to apply the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
On the other hand, bank managers who are in a bad position and are waiting for government help can expect that their severance pay, simply called the golden parachute over the Atlantic, will be capped by the government.
The ceiling on wages is mentioned only in very specific cases, and the limits depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the enterprise.
The capping principle means that if the Treasury secretariat buys at auction, they'll levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Right after the buyback of the bad loans, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the rulers is not overstated.
To complete the picture, it should be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified, the ceiling only applies to new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
"This is the first time in US history that there will be legal limits on the appointment of CEOs", said the chairman of the House of Representatives Financial Services Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they can even be winners in the matter as soon as the economy and with it the banks rescued fall back on their feet.
The bill states that within the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal that will determine how losses will be reimbursed to taxpayers, starting with the financial sector.
On both sides, there were those who expressed doubts about this plan.
"This is not what the American people mandated us to do, this is not protecting taxpayer dollars", said Rep. Darrell Issa, a Republican from California.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, thinks that it's the same people who are pushing for action that are responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, according to the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared with the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared with the previous year.
Domestic industrial selling prices increased only slightly, by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic selling prices in the manufacturing sectors rose only slightly, by 0.1%, compared with July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with the manufacture of bags and belts in first place with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by footwear production with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing of products and chemicals sector (1.6%).
This resulted in a deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent) and a slight increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices of paper production, printing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of manufacturing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a large proportion of national industrial output, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales in the processing sectors, the most significant price increases (32.4%) were in the oil processing sector.
In the manufacture of metal products, there was a price increase of 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices rose by 11 per cent.
Price decreases were recorded in the textile and textile products manufacturing sectors (2.5 per cent) and in the machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing sector (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of manufacturing industry, the price increase ranged from 0.6 to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole of the processing industry, prices rose by 10.2 per cent in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the groups of domestic trade and by sector allocation, the sectors generating profit on investment showed the most significant monthly price increase in August (0.7 per cent).
In the sectors producing consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while those of the sectors producing energy and materials for further processing were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest increase was observed in the energy and materials for further processing production sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-generating sectors, it fell by 1.4 per cent.
Industrial export sales prices, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7% against the euro and by 7.1% against the dollar, and compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5% against the euro and by 15.9% against the dollar.
