Járóka said: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, hosted by France as the representative of the current Presidency of the European Union, began in Paris.
In her message to the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP for the European People's Party Fidesz, drew attention to segregation in education, as it is a violation of the law that affects Roma children the most and is therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, the French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, the European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of European legal protection and civil organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the Fidesz PP group press office, Járóka warned that apart from the discrimination in hiring, Roma are disappearing from the labour market, primarily because of their low qualifications.
"The overwhelming majority of Roma youths do not have a high school diploma, and as a result of a poor basic education, only a tiny fraction have the opportunity to obtain a higher education qualification".
The Commission has also been asked to present a proposal for a regulation on the establishment of a European Agency for the Evaluation of Competition (EAEACEC) and to propose to the Council that the Commission should be able to submit a proposal for a regulation on the establishment of a European Agency for the Evaluation of Competition (EACEC).
Investing in early education for Roma children means strengthening the economies of the European Union member countries.
The Commission's proposal is to make the European Parliament responsible for the implementation of the directive.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through the taxes paid from his income and consumption, he contributes to the state budget.
"Because of their EU citizenship, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education and protected from poor quality and sectarian education", stressed Lívia Járóka.
The Commission is proposing to extend the scope of the directive to include the right to vote and stand as a candidate in elections to the European Parliament and to the European Parliament.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give Roma children the opportunities guaranteed by democracy so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe", Járóka said.
In the name of the 'European Year of Equal Opportunities' for all, the aim of the European Equal Opportunities Summit, which has been held annually since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures taken for equal opportunities and the fight against discrimination at European level and at the level of the Member States.
