No opposition MPs entered the Belarusian parliament after Sunday's elections.
According to Russian observers, this is due to a country led by Alexander Lukashenko, which ensures prosperity and stability, while according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), this is due to irregularities committed during the counting of votes.
The OSCE, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, does not recognise the elections.
Although the 110-member legislature in this country of 10 million people has been doing without opposition for decades, before yesterday's elections, the opposition uniting under the name United Democratic Forces (UDF) was seriously hoping that Lukashenko, renewing his presidency for the fourth time in a dubious election, following the amendment of the constitution in 2006, would "allow" some opposition members of parliament this time.
In this way, the ODSZ has abandoned its originally planned boycott.
The fact that Belarus, increasingly dependent on Russia, would want to improve its relations with the EU, where Lukashenko and several high-ranking politicians are denied entry visas because of the anti-democratic Belarusian political order, was one of the opposition's expectations.
The fact that the OSCE, in evaluating the campaign, emphasised positive changes rather than shortcomings, such as the prohibition on running for one third of the opposition candidates, referred to a previous appeasement.
However, the OSCE press release on Monday already disputed the campaign, during which most of the opposition candidates could not appear in the media, and in particular the fact that the opposition could not be present during the counting of votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is still feeling a palpable improvement in the political regime: the political prisoners have been released, and Minsk is ready for small confrontations with Moscow, still refusing to recognize South Ossetia and Abkhazia as separate from Georgia, while Russia, with which Belarus forms a confederation on paper, has considered the two territories independent for a month already.
"We have taken two steps forward and one step back, but the most important thing is that the dialogue has been started between Belarus and the EU", Alexander Milinkevich told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential elections, it is desirable that this should remain so, despite the fact that "the government was afraid to bring even one opponent into this parliament, which has no weight".
The opposition does not plan to protest the results, but instead is trying to get the message of economic reforms across to voters.
"Of course, we have a lot of concerns in this area: we have to print our opposition newspapers in Russia, the local authorities are putting a stick in our sails in terms of distribution, but I can also see that they are increasingly supporting the elections, even in the circle of the elderly people" - said Milinkevitch, referring to the fact that in the current Lukashenko regime, which considers social security as its main result, the layer of the retired who support it officially really do not consider it appropriate anymore.
"Because of the country's debt and the rising trade deficit, the collapse of social security, 'evocating the silence of a cemetery', is now only a matter of time", Milinkevitch said.
Unlike the opposition politician, Russian observers described the elections as democratic.
Sergey Lebedev, head of the mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told the Russian news agency Ria Novosti: "People don't believe in words, but in deeds".
