Accidents at work, Napolitano: 'Prevention is crucial'
Every day in Italy there are 2,500 work accidents, 3 deaths and 27 people who remain permanently disabled.
In 2007, Inail data confirmed that the white deaths were about 1,200.
The figures show the seriousness of the phenomenon that remains one of the main causes of death, causing almost twice as many deaths as homicides.
To draw the attention of the institutions, social forces and the media to this tragic issue, Anmil is celebrating the 58th National Day of the Victims of Work Accidents, which is now celebrated on the second Sunday of October, in all the Italian provinces.
"The worrying data released by Anmil, as well as the tragic events of the last few days, confirm the importance of the subject of prevention in the workplace", says the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, in a message sent to the President of Anmil, National Association of the maimed and disabled of work, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his sincere appreciation for the continuing effort of the association to promote prevention at the workplace, the protection of injured workers, assistance to the families of the victims and the raising of public awareness.
"Naturally outraged, everyone has joined in to put an end to such tragedies which, by their scale, arouse the outcry of the media and the participation of public opinion, even though daily reality presents us with dramatic cases, even repetitive in their dynamic.
Napolitano does not hide that "there is certainly a problem of resources: it is essential to invest in training and information"
The many initiatives promoted in the school sector are of particular importance for a more direct awareness on the part of young people entering the world of work.
It is our duty to keep an eye on this phenomenon, not to underestimate the alarm about the social gravity, to apply and improve the legislative norms.
The House's President Gianfranco Fini stressed that "the phenomenon of white deaths is an absolute social emergency, which offends the conscience of each of us, and requires all institutions to make a concrete effort to put an end to it quickly".
The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight positive trend, but this does not prevent the number of white deaths from being impressive", said later Pietro Mercandelli, President of Anmil.
"we don't want this 'discounting' to translate into in fact, a minor attention, because it is precisely when the attention relaxes, that tragedy happens.
