They point to the MP3 player, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent damage to hearing.
This is the message from the European Commission, which in a communiqué issued in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Unanticipated and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"This scientific report", we read in the footnote, "shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at high volume using portable music devices for more than one hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss.
"I am concerned that so many young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably", says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data", the EU official continued, "this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies.'
The independent scientific committee was asked by Brussels to look into the problem, given the intensive use of portable music equipment and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise it generates.
'The scientists confirm that there is good cause for concern and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about the hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week exceed the current limits for the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for extended periods of time risk permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
The Commission has therefore decided to send the Commission to Rome for the future of the capital.
Today we start, in March we finish, in June we draw the sums.
