The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon was already manifest a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this, reporting that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to the federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, in fact, which has made itself felt in a despotic way with the vote I mentioned at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the great changes, which the current economic earthquake is foreshadowing or already causing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the phenomena that have been suppressed for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualisation, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with the outside world, but which, above all, involve the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be global economically but politically it is almost only national.
Political internationalisation seems to be out of the question, or at least has little to say: the clear proof is provided by the European Union which, divided as usual between the various interests and the various national strategies, is unable to decide on a common policy.
And so it is from the government of each State that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a love of credits: when we go through a difficult period, it is only the States that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them - two invaluable resources, which no market or international organisation can ever have in a comparable way.
This new emphasis on the crisis of the nation-state is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the still greater importance which more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would, on the contrary, have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather non-material things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely bound to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than who is not, that is, who has the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second innovation, which, however, involves a break.
Which means territory, state, government, inevitably means politics, and therefore leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discrediting of existing leadership, economic specimens that have proven inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And then, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of alienation that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now in their apogee, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership is underground, fuelling a powerful and widespread movement of delegitimisation of the ruling classes and the traditional political orders, which is manifested in the improvised electoral 'revolts' or, in the changes of collective mood of recent times, from the rise of the conservatives in Bavaria, to the fall of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the US Congress against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the Right in Italy did not come by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, are having more and more difficulty, which is not new, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and potentially agitates in an exorbitant way.
In view of all this, to speak of a current "mass rebellion" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But as they say, keep your eyes wide open, and for good reason.
Superglue for walking on walls.
Defying the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, walking on walls like Spiderman.
That is the goal of various American research centers, and today a team of four institutes is almost there.
With a glue measuring just one square inch [2.5 cm], researchers were able to hold a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the research team, is an evolution of the ones we know of that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the gecko's feet, which are covered with microscopic hairs that provide the animal with a perfect grip.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, it is easily detachable from the wall", says Lim Daiing, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe it's for walking on walls like Spider-Man? Maybe it is, but the researchers are thinking about a much less fascinating use, such as connecting between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at this time.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal American Chemical Society, researchers in California presented a hairlike microfiber adhesive that cleans itself of dust when moved across a surface to ensure perfect and consistent adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juice.
Watch out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing their effectiveness, depending on the case, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, Professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, warns of the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, when taken in conjunction with certain medicines. At the American Chemical Society's 236th National Meeting in Philadelphia, he is sounding a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines, negating their beneficial effects and putting the health of patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has been heavily criticized for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-aging and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
The Italian Medicines Agency itself had given the news in an information bulletin two years ago, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mixture and to be careful what they drink, if they take medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
According to experts, even orange and apple juice contain substances that inhibit medication.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, head of the pharmacology department of the Public University of Milan: "these findings are generally reported immediately to the various national and international agencies of medicines who will have to change the information notes of the medicines if necessary.
It is always advisable to read the instructions for the medicines you are taking and, if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but clearly contact the doctor or pharmacist", the expert stressed to the Ansa agency.
