Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
Today is the release of OpenOffice.org.3, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from the home to the office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the more popular Microsoft Office.
Following almost a year's work by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office package is presented to the general public with various novelties: from the welcome screen, and the revised and less austere interface, to more important ones, such as the compatibility born for the Apple Mac OS X operating system, and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some specific functions for certain modules, such as the one that allows to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphic development module, preserving the original appearance of the page.
It is also possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents which combine the typical graphic of the Adobe format with elements of a spreadsheet or a word processor.
Collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements inside the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on the changes, in the elaboration of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some of the features of OpenOffice to the web (on the cloud), and in the next few weeks, they should release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded from http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and is added to the English version which was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can be sent to the home or workplace on request.
And if the theme of free can be a way to spread it in homes, it is precisely in business that the Open Office suite is trying the big challenge, already being able to count on various projects carried out in public administration and schools.
In addition, the realities that offer a training, consultancy and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which could also be open to business prospects.
Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the video writing equivalent of Word; Calc, the spreadsheet intended to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint's rival presentations; Dbase, such as the famous Access, is the program that allows working on databases; finally Drwa is the graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today we have almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure
