Goodbye old Paradiso cinema, the cities are enlightening the historical theaters.
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore is a good illustration of what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial towns,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the emergence of large multiplexes on the periphery and the death of single-screen cinemas in the city centres, is one of the major events that seems to us to be unavoidable and unquestionable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that gives Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prize of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of experiencing cinema, can be lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, say it all: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and theatres in the main cities have paid the most for this: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romagna is at the top with 82 lost single-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that the multiplex is the main reason for their disappearance is that the three Italian regions have registered the most new multiplex cinemas: 195 more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian cinema industry has grown irrationally", observes Paolo Protti, president of ANAC, "and it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a cinema hall closes in a city, not all of its patrons are necessarily willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of credit for the merchants: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector, it would require between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
The first Italian city to be concerned about these closures was Bologna, which decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between the City Council and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-screen cinemas in historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the measures envisaged are tax concessions for the managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking lots and certain car parks.
"This is an initiative that I like", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example and implement other measures.
It is clear, however, that to counter the super power of multiplexes, traditional theatres must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audiences are more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradiso Cinema" which I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now closed, where I lived so many shared emotions, I turn the other way so I don't see the dust-blackened signs.
