When energy is born from waves, now the big ones are going.
This is a vast deposit that covers over 70 percent of the surface of the planet and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have set their eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of harnessing energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970's, with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now environmental authorities and the new increase in oil are giving a great boost to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity demand could be met by systems that exploit ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there'd be the tides and currents.
Colossians on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in the north of Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it was a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more of these companies, which have always been devoted to traditional energy, are turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is exploring opportunities to cooperate with us".
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit by the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially when you consider that in Alaska, the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavation
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are pursuing the path of energy from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate, observers say, a growing interest.
Technology to be worked out.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, as marine energy does not allay fears about its environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not appear to pose a major problem to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, we must use technologies with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The wave-like pressure that moves the mud up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn, powers a generator.
The power is sent to shore through undersea cables.
At the moment, we have four systems of this type in the design phase, one pending federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, in contrast, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking garage using six undersea turbines from the East River in New York City.
The movement of water on the tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that powers a generator.
Verdant announced that they have a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to pump energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, is the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than the wind, the sun, or the waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it's precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, and others, are looking to the coast, investing $7.5 million in 2008 and planning investments up to $35 million in 2009.
